FBIS4-57861 "drlat102_m_94005" FBIS-LAT-94-102 Daily Report 25 May 1994 Brazil U.S., French Firms Win Sivam Project Bid U.S., French Firms Win Sivam Project Bid PY2605022994 Sao Paulo O ESTADO DE SAO PAULO in Portuguese 25 May 94 p A6 PY2605022994 Sao Paulo O ESTADO DE SAO PAULO Portuguese BFN [From the "O ESTADO Column" by Cristiana Lobo] [Text] On 24 May, Strategic Affairs Secretary Mario Cesar Flores informed President Itamar Franco of the result of an international bid for the implementation of Sivam, the Amazon Region Surveillance System. This has been the largest bid ever held in Brazil, with companies from 10 countries participating. The project costs amount to $1.1 billion and will be implemented over eight years. The winners of the tender are a U.S. consortium led by Raytheon and a French consortium led by the state-owned Thomson and Alcatel companies. A German consortium led by Dasa was selected as "an alternate." The loser was a consortium formed by Unisys and IBM, the two largest U.S. computer companies.
